{{Infobox person | pre-nominals = | name = Alice von Hildebrand <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | post-nominals = | honorific_suffix = [[Order of St. Gregory the Great|DCSG]] | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pronunciation = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1923|03|11}} | birth_place = [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] | baptised = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered --> | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | burial_place = <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates (displays "Burial place" as label) --> | burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | education = | alma_mater = [[Fordham University]] | occupation = philosopher, theologian, professor, lecturer, author | employer = [[Hunter College]] | notable_works = <!-- produces label "Notable work"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label "Notable credit(s)"; or by |works=, which produces label "Works"; or by |label_name=, which produces label "Label(s)" --> | spouse = [[Dietrich von Hildebrand]] <!-- Use article title or common name --> | children = | relatives = | family = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''Alice M. von Hildebrand''', [[Order of St. Gregory the Great|DCSG]]<ref name=DVHLP>{{cite web | url=http://www.hildebrandproject.org/about/alice-von-hildebrand | title=Alice von Hildebrand | last= | first= | author= | authorlink= | date= | year= | website= | series= | publisher=Dietrich von Hildebrand Legacy Project | work= | location= | page= | pages= | at= | language= | trans_title= | type= | format= | arxiv= | asin= | bibcode= | doi= | doi_brokendate= | isbn= | issn= | jfm= | jstor= | lccn= | mr= | oclc= | ol= | osti= | pmc= | pmid= | rfc= | ssrn= | zbl= |id= | archiveurl= | archivedate= | deadurl= | accessdate=April 14, 2018 | quote= | ref= | separator= | postscript= | subscription= | registration= }}</ref> is a [[Catholicism|Catholic]] [[philosopher]], [[theologian]], lecturer, author, and former professor; she is also the second wife of [[Dietrich von Hildebrand]].
==Background== Alicia M. Jourdain was on born on March 11, 1923, in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]).
==Career== Von Hildebrand moved to the [[United States]] in 1940 and began teaching at [[Hunter College]] in [[New York City]] in 1947.<ref name=DVHLP />
Von Hildebrand revealed that [[Bella Dodd]], a friend of her and her husband who reverted to Catholicism in April 1952, had confessed privately to them and also publicly at a conference in [[Orange, California]] that [[Bella Dodd#Catholic Church|she had assisted with a communist infiltration of Catholic seminaries]].<ref name=CMinterview>{{cite AV media | people= | date=January 29, 2016 | title=The Vortex—Infiltration! | trans-title= | medium=[[YouTube]] video | language= | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKLBvvlabgw | access-date=April 14, 2018 | archive-url= | archive-date= | format= | time= | location= | publisher=[[Michael Voris|Church Militant]] | id= | isbn= | oclc= | quote= | ref= }}</ref>
Von Hildebrand has also criticized the advance of [[relativism]]<ref name=TANBooks>{{cite book | last1=von Hildebrand | first1=Alice | author-link1= | last2=Crosby | first2=John Henry | author-link2= | display-authors= | author-mask= | last-author-amp= | date= | year= | orig-year=2014 | editor1-last= | editor1-first= | editor1-link= | display-editors= | title=Memoirs of a Happy Failure | script-title= | trans-title= | url=https://www.tanbooks.com/index.php/memoirs-of-a-happy-failure-3.html | dead-url= | format= | type= | series= | language= | volume= | issue= | others= | edition= | location= | publisher=Saint Benedictine Press | publication-date= | page= | pages= | at= | nopp= | arxiv= | asin= | bibcode= | doi= | doi-broken-date= | isbn=978-1-618901-26-2 | issn= | jfm= | jstor= | lccn= | mr= | oclc= | ol= | osti= | pmc= | pmid= | rfc= | ssrn= | zbl= | id= | archive-url= | archive-date= | access-date= | via= | registration= | subscription= | lay-summary= | lay-source= | lay-date= | quote= | name-list-format= | mode= | postscript= | ref= }}</ref> and [[modernism in the Catholic Church]], particularly within its institutions of [[Catholic higher education]] and its [[Catholic school]]s.<ref name=CMinterview />
Von Hildebrand retired in 1984.<ref name=DVHLP /> She lives in the United States and is a lecturer and author.<ref name=DVHLP /> She has made more than 80 appearances on [[EWTN]] television programming.<ref name=DVHLP /> In 2004 she launched the Dietrich von Hildebrand Legacy Project with some of her husband's former students.<ref name=DVHLP /> Her works include ''The Soul of a Lion: The Life of Dietrich von Hildebrand'' (2000), a biography of her husband, and her autobiography, ''Memoirs of a Happy Failure'' (2014),<ref name=TANBooks /> which recounts her escape from [[Nazism|Nazi]] [[Europe]] and her teaching career at Hunter College.
Von Hildebrand is a Dame Commander of the Order of St. Gregory the Great, a papal knighthood.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
==Personal life== In 1959, Jourdain married philosopher and theologian [[Dietrich von Hildebrand]] (1889–1977), having met him at [[Fordham University]] in New York City, where she was a student and he was a professor. (Dietrich von Hildebrand's first wife had died in 1957.). They remained married until his death.
